<TEXT>
gov gaston caperton presented striking 
teachers tuesday night with a sevenpoint plan that promises no pay 
raises but calls for a special legislative session if theres 
enough surplus money to fund a salary increase 
caperton also offered to call an education summit in may to 
seek longterm solutions to the annual problem of teacher pay 
teacher union representatives left the governors office without 
comment about 1045 pm tuesday following a second day of talks 
gubernatorial spokesman gc morse said the administration 
expects an answer from the west virginia education association and 
the west virginia federation of teachers by noon wednesday 
the immediate reaction from these folks was favorable but 
these folks need to get back and confer with whoever they confer 
with morse said 
the governor announced his offer in a statement at 11 pm 
tuesday he took no questions from reporters 
on march 5 when the legislature was still in session the 
governor and legislative leaders offered the teachers a 5 percent 
pay raise financed by a tax increase for coal producers but that 
deal collapsed the next day 
caperton said tuesday night that he would not propose a tax 
increase again because the public wouldnt support it 
west virginia simply cannot afford to do more caperton 
said no matter how jusitifed their position may be on the matter 
of teacher compensation i bear a responsibility to the taxpayers 
of west virginia 
more than 85 percent of west virginias 22000 public 
schoolteachers walked out in the states first such strike last 
wednesday in a dispute over wages and benefits by tuesday the 
strike had spread to 46 of the states 55 counties 
the wvea claims 16000 members statewide and the wvft had 
3000 including teachers and other school employees 
in addition to the special session proposal and the education 
summit the governors proposal includes 
an offer to work with teacher representatives to come up with 
legislative proposals 
3 million from a school computer program to be diverted to 
teacher pay 
a promise to continue to work for equity funding aimed at 
equalizing teacher salaries statewide including 20 million this 
year 
full funding of the state health insurance program with no 
deductibles or copayments and without benefit reductions 
full funding of the teachers retirement system 
caperton called the meetings with the teacher representatives 
cordial and fruitful 
and although we have not yet reached a final agreement on 
returning teachers to the classrooms we have closed the distance 
between ourselves and that goal caperton said 
earlier in the day caperton postponed a speech on education 
policy he was due to deliver tuesday because of the continuing 
discussions his office said in a statement the speech was 
rescheduled for wednesday night 
morse said at least part of the reason was because the governor 
had very little sleep monday night after holding talks for seven 
hours 
while the two sides gathered around a table in the governors 
conference room at the capitol on tuesday teachers walked picket 
lines at various places around the state 
the state department of education said schools were closed 
tuesday in 25 counties open in 19 and mixed in 11 others the 
number of teachers and students affected was not immediately 
available said education spokeswoman carolyn spangler 
teachers in greenbrier county agreed tuesday night to return to 
work beginning monday the school board which had threatened to 
fire teachers who failed to report for work wednesday said it 
would withdraw letters threatening the dismissals 
in jefferson county teachers face fines and a contempt of court 
citation if they dont return to work by thursday but the teachers 
said they would ask the state supreme court on wednesday to halt an 
injunction ordering them back to work 
spangler said several counties have discussed seeking court 
injunctions to limit pickets 
the states average teacher salary is 21904 less than 
teachers in every state except arkansas and south dakota according 
to the national education association 
</TEXT>
