<TEXT>
jimmy carter the architect of the camp 
david peace accords said tuesday he doesnt expect the collapse of 
israels government to ruin chances for a palestinianisraeli 
dialogue and eventual peace in the middle east 
the former president said he hopes a singleparty government 
will emerge from israels political turmoil to avoid the timidity 
and stalemate of coalition government 
i do think there is still a good chance for dialogue 
carter said after a meeting with president hosni mubarak 
the basic parameters have been worked out he said 
theres agreement among the palestinians the egyptians the 
americans and i think more than half the israelis so i believe 
its going to happen it may be delayed to some degree 
tuesday israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir fired his finance 
minister and political adversary shimon peres ten ministers from 
peres leftleaning labor party followed their leader out of the 
cabinet and the tenuous political alliance that has ruled israel 
for six years collapsed 
the government fell due to clashes over us proposals for an 
israelipalestinian dialogue 
labor has accepted the idea of talking to palestinian deportees 
and arab residents of israeliannexed east jerusalem 
but likud opposes both ideas saying they will lead to indirect 
talks with the palestine liberation organization and compromise 
israeli control over a united jerusalem israel considers the plo 
to be a terrorist group and refuses to have a dialogue with it 
following peres dismissal and the mass resignation of his party 
colleagues israel faces eventual elections 
im no expert on israeli politics but ive always had the 
feeling that a leadership of either likud or labor is better than 
having a coalition government carter said 
he said he was discouraged in may 1977 when menachem begin led 
his likud bloc to its first electoral victory since israels 
statehood in 1948 
i never believed that the likud under him would move forward 
in a courageous way toward peace the former president said 
but begin later joined carter and egypts former president anwar 
sadat in signing the camp david accords of 1978 which led a year 
later to the first and only peace treaty between israel and an arab 
nation 
so i dont really think it matters one way or another which 
party ultimately triumphs even if the likud should triumph i 
think this might bode better for a strong move towards peace than 
to have a stalemated coalition government carter said 
carter is on a private four nation tour of the middle east 
after leaving egypt he is to visit syria israel and jordan 
since leaving office carter has visited the middle east four 
times to monitor peace efforts 
</TEXT>
