<TEXT>
a federal judge issued a limited ruling tuesday 
backing the internal revenue services efforts to force lawyers to 
identify clients who pay them more than 10000 in cash 
us district judge vincent l broderick said two manhattan law 
firms must reveal the identities of five such clients but stayed 
his order so that attorneys ronald fischetti and paul goldberger 
could appeal 
he emphasized however that other lawyers could be exempt 
because of special circumstances 
the judge said that as the law now stands the issue must be 
decided on a casebycase basis he urged the irs and the us 
justice department to work with the defense bar to set up 
guidelines for lawyers reporting cash income 
at issue is a 1984 law that requires everyone in trade or 
business to report cash receipts of more than 10000 and the 
source of the payments 
lawyers maintain that the law violates the attorneyclient 
privilege 
fischetti goldberger and their firms were the subjects of the 
first civil lawsuits to be brought in an enforcement campaign 
against lawyers by the irs last week the irs sent summonses to 90 
other attorneys demanding similar information 
both fischetti and goldberger who have handled many organized 
crime and drug cases filled out the required forms but refused to 
identify five clients who paid them more than 10000 in 1986 and 
1987 
in his oral ruling broderick did not specify what special 
circumstances could exempt lawyers from identifying clients on the 
irs forms 
neil sonnett a miami lawyer who is president of the national 
association of criminal defense lawyers said an exemption could be 
made when an attorney is actively representing a client who is 
under indictment 
sonnett said that in the cases of fischetti and goldberger 
their representation of the clients whose identities were being 
sought had already concluded 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

