<TEXT>
the supreme court is likely to announce soon 
possibly monday whether it will grant a bush administration 
request for speededup review of a new law making it a crime to 
burn the american flag 
the justices in recess this week will meet in a private 
conference friday to consider the request and could announce a 
decision when they return to the bench 
the justice department while expressing doubts about the laws 
constitutionality filed legal papers with the court tuesday urging 
it to move rapidly and uphold the law 
department lawyers called for expedited consideration of the 
politically charged issue proposing oral arguments before the 
court april 25 that would permit the justices to rule before the 
current term ends in july 
the department urged the high court to overturn rulings by two 
judges in washington and in seattle who declared the law 
unconstitutional 
the judges overvalued the narrow category of expressive 
conduct at stake and undervalued the compelling governmental 
interest that lies at the core of the statute the preservation of 
the flag as the unique symbol of our nation the department said 
conviction under the law carries a oneyear jail sentence 
the justice department acknowledged that president bush allowed 
the law to be enacted last oct 28 without his signature because he 
questions its constitutionality and prefers a constitutional 
amendment to assure the same protection for the flag 
bush said he has serious doubts the law can withstand 
supreme court review and said a constitutional amendment is the 
only way to ensure that our flag is protected from desecration 
a lawyer representing the defendants in both flag cases accused 
the administration of seeking expedited supreme court review so 
that the flag will be an issue in this years campaign for house 
and senate seats 
if the court issues its decision in july and its in our 
favor there is no doubt a constitutional amendment will be 
introduced in congress said david cole an attorney with the 
center for constitutional rights 
cole said he will ask the court not to consider the case until 
october because this is a very important constitutional question 
it shouldnt be subject to political considerations 
the supreme court voting 54 last june struck down a texas law 
barring desecration or destruction of the flag the court said 
burning the american flag as a form of political protest is 
protected by the constitutions free speech guarantees 
that case echoed themes from the 1988 presidential campaign in 
which bush stressed patriotic values and attacked his democratic 
opponent gov michael dukakis of massachusetts for vetoing state 
legislation to require that public schoolteachers lead their 
classes in the pledge of allegiance 
the june supreme court decision touched off a political 
firestorm and ultimately led to enactment of the new 
flagprotection law 
democratic leaders in congress supported the law as an 
alternative to a constitutional amendment 
in recent decisions federal judges in washington and in seattle 
dismissed criminal charges against defendants accused of flag 
burning saying the new law violated their free speech rights 
in the washington case three demonstrators were arrested on 
oct 30 after they set several flags on fire during a protest 
outside the us capitol 
four demonstrators were charged with burning a flag outside a 
seattle post office the previous day 
the justice department brief was signed by solicitor general 
kenneth w starr the administrations top courtroom attorney and 
other department lawyers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

