<TEXT>
federal safety officials are calling for 6000 
new york city subway cars to be equipped with speedometers after 
finding that some were going 15 miles per hour faster than the 
operators thought 
the recommendation came in a national transportation safety 
board meeting tuesday on a crash in which a train carrying 
passengers bumped into a farecollection train at the 103rd street 
station in uptown manhattan on march 10 1989 forty people were 
injured one seriously 
older subway systems in new york boston and philadelphia are 
the only ones in the country without speed indicators on the cars 
said the boards senior rail accident investigator william pugh 
more modern systems are controlled by computers that 
automatically report and control train speed and keep trains spaced 
apart 
the ntsb voted 40 to blame the crash on the unauthorized use of 
a jumper cable that caused signal lights in the station to 
malfunction a light had indicated the station was clear of trains 
investigators said 
the board said the fact the train was going faster than the 
posted 18 mph contributed to the seriousness of the crash but it 
did not blame the operator for the excessive speed saying the new 
york city transit authority failed to furnish a reasonable means 
for operators to determine speed 
damage from the crash totaled 360000 
pugh said checks of new york subways with radar guns found that 
operators usually underestimated their speed often by as much as 
15 mph 
he estimated that retrofitting all of new yorks cars with 
speedometers would cost about 6 million equipping new cars as 
they are added to the system would cost less 
upgrading the 450mile system with computer controls that 
operate most of the nations subway system would cost more than 1 
billion pugh said 
board member jim burnett suggested cars might also be equipped 
with recorders to aid transit officials and investigators in 
determining the speed of cars but the board elected to ask for 
installation of speed indicators first 
the safety panel recommended a change in the design of the 
operator cabin door it said the operator was trapped inside and 
had to be pulled out through a window 
it also called for the transit authority to develop a procedure 
for notifying train operators when an unscheduled train is placed 
in front of them schedules of fare collection trains which travel 
from station to station to pick up cash are not posted for 
security reasons investigators said 
</TEXT>
