<TEXT>
psychoanalyst bruno bettelheim a student of 
sigmund freud who taught that violent fantasies and fairy tales 
were part of a healthy childs psychology killed himself at a 
nursing home at age 86 authorities said 
bettelheim died tuesday of suicidal asphyxiation at the charter 
house in silver spring md said dr john e smialek marylands 
medical examiner smialek declined to give details friends said 
bettelheim recently had suffered a stroke 
a survivor of the nazi death camps bettelheim came to the 
united states during world war ii and became a pioneer in treating 
childhood mental disturbances his vivid writings reached millions 
of readers 
from 1944 to 1973 bettelheim ran the sonia shankman orthogenic 
school for disturbed children at the university of chicago 
he had a marvelous talent for being able to see the world 
through the eyes of the other even if the other was a tremendously 
bizzare person said jacquelyn sanders who took over the school 
when bettelheim retired he was able to see the world through 
that persons eyes so that person no longer became bizzare 
and he was able to write about them in the way people could 
understand 
the uses of enchantment written with karen zelan in 1976 
won bettelheim the national book award and the national book 
critics circle award 
in it he held that fairy tales represent the struggle for 
identity that children wage against their parents hostile 
fantasies toward parents can be safely channeled through enjoyment 
of punishment inflicted on witches and demons 
a december review in the chicago tribune of his last book 
freuds vienna and other essays noted bettelheims shrewd 
grasp of the sometimes petty human circumstance behind the grand 
achievement 
for example bettelheim admitted becoming interested in freuds 
theories at age 13 in order to impress a girl 
bettelheim was born aug 28 1903 in vienna and studied there 
under freud a jew he was sent to the dachau and buchenwald 
concentration camps after his release in 1939 he gained early 
fame for his study of death camp prisoners 
in surviving an essay published in the new yorker in 1976 
he said prisoners who survived were those who lived not for lifes 
sake but for some cultural ideal that transcended them 
at the orthogenic school bettelheim insisted on constant 
attention for severely disturbed children and stayed there from 
early morning until after midnight nearly every day said benjamin 
wright a former colleague 
he would not take no for an answer no matter how difficult the 
child was said wright 
the schools success stories include several college professors 
authors and a stockbroker he said 
dr raymond fowler chief executive of the american 
psychological association in washington said bettelheims 1950 
book on his experiences at the school love is not enough 
influenced fowler to become a psychologist 
some of bettelheims theories were criticized as overly harsh on 
parents he contended at one time that mentally ill mothers were 
responsible for autism in children 
he softened his views in the 1987 book a good enough parent 
a book on childrearing which said parents are innately good 
enough to raise children 
bettelheim became professor emeritus at the university of 
chicago in 1975 
he told me that once you were in a camp you could never 
escape the cruelty a longtime colleague and friend rudolf 
ekstein told the new york times he turned it upside down when 
he started his school for disturbed children it was a protected 
caring environment the mirror opposite of the camps 
his other works included dynamics of prejudice 1950 
truants from life 1955 the informed heart 1960 and 
the children of the dream 1969 
bettelheims wife gertrud weinfeld died in 1984 he is 
survived by three children 
funeral arrangements were not immediately known 
</TEXT>
