that a time lapse of eight to 10 years exists between the time new 
techniques are developed and the time they are used in dental 
offices 
the laser being studied at the university of detroit vaporizes 
tooth decay without the noise vibration or smell often associated 
with dental drills 
truhe said lasers also decrease the chances of tooth decay 
returning around fillings 
but while lasers can penetrate dentin the second level of 
tooth covering they have not been able yet to pass through the 
hardest and outermost tooth layer enamel 
also truhe said the us food and drug administration so far 
has approved lasers only for use on soft tissues 
still there is little doubt truhe said that lasers will be 
the standard of care for repairing dental cavities by the year 2000 
also electronic anesthesia machines have been developed to 
deaden pain through battery power the fdaapproved machines 
already are in use in some dentists offices and are still being 
researched at the university of colorado 
the machines employ electrical impulses that travel through 
battery wires to small adhesive pads attached to the patients 
mouth 
truhe explained that the impulses deaden pain by flooding nerves 
with nonpainful stimuli so that painful stimuli cannot pass 
through the impulses also increase the brains production of 
painlessening chemicals such as serotonin and endorphins 
