<TEXT>
the vatican today restored the leadership of 
the longpersecuted roman catholic church in romania and revived 
the eastern rite branch that was suppressed there more than 40 
years ago 
pope john paul ii appointed 12 bishops to restore the strength 
the church enjoyed before a crackdown on religion began in 1948 
it marked the biggest step forward by the vatican in eastern 
europe since the former hardline regimes began to crumble last 
year 
vatican spokesman joaquin navarro said the church was 
overjoyed by the moves in romania and hinted that a restoration 
of diplomatic relations with bucharest cut by the communists in 
1950 was not far off 
romanian clergy have also invited the pope to visit the country 
but navarro said no date has been fixed 
the appointments were made possible by the actions of romanian 
authorities in january suspending 1948 decrees that sharply 
curtailed the freedom of roman catholics and forcibly incorporated 
the eastern or byzantine rite catholic church into the orthodox 
church 
their 1800 churches were confiscated and bishops and priests 
who refused to accept the merger were jailed a situation similar 
to that in the ukraine 
in recent days vatican officials have been in the soviet union 
to negotiate with soviet and orthodox church authorities on the 
revival of the ukrainian catholic church 
but there has been no action taken yet on a law guaranteeing 
freedom of religion which would legalize the ukrainian catholic 
church and was promised by president mikhail s gorbachev when he 
met with the pope here in december 
two of the new eastern rite bishops in romania are in their late 
70s or past the normal vatican retirement age navarro said the 
nominations were in recognition for their suffering for the church 
both had been imprisoned for years and one of them bishop 
alexander todea 77 of alba julia had been sentenced to death in 
1951 and freed in a 1964 amnesty 
all had practiced their religion underground in what the vatican 
calls the catacomb church 
the vatican estimates there are 28 million catholics from the 
two rites in romania 
the nominations restore the roman and eastern rite churches in 
romania to their pre1948 strength of six and five bishops 
respectively before today only two roman dioceses were headed by 
bishops 
navarro stressed the nominations were made independently by the 
pope with no interference by the romanian government 
over the past year the vatican has reestablished diplomatic 
relations with poland and hungary 
