adjusted 7959 billion after falling a revised 04 percent in 
december 
the december drop originally reported to be 02 percent was 
the first since a 01 percent decline in october 1988 and the 
largest since a 06 percent fall in december 1986 
business sales meanwhile rose to a seasonally adjusted 5230 
billion after falling a revised 02 percent in december december 
sales originally were reported to be unchanged from november 
the january business activity produced a 152 ratio of 
inventories to sales the same as in december that means that it 
would take 152 months to exhaust inventories at the january pace 
the ratio was 153 in both october and november 
inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as 
output exceeds demand if they were to pile up excessively it 
could mean cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs 
however economists do not feel the ratio is at a dangerous 
level 
retail backlogs fell 06 percent in january while sales rose 
28 percent 
part of the improvement in retail inventories came as automobile 
companies temporarily laid off thousands of workers during the 
month to trim the number of motor vehicles stuck on backlots auto 
inventories dropped 36 percent 
manufacturing inventories rose 07 percent while sales dropped 
19 percent 
wholesalers inventories edged up 02 percent while their sales 
gained 14 percent 
