<TEXT>
approval of the united states space program is 
at an alltime high but fewer than two out of three americans 
favor the lunar base and mars missions proposed by president bush 
according to a survey released today 
eighty percent of the american people favor the space program 
said the nationwide telephone poll of 1200 registered voters 
conducted by market opinion research the poll was commissioned by 
rockwell international corporation one of the biggest aerospace 
manufacturers and builder of the space shuttles 
the survey which has a margin of error of plus or minus 28 
percent showed approval rating of the space program continuing to 
rise from 56 percent in may 1978 the space station which is 
entering the building phase was favored by 74 percent of those 
polled up from 69 percent last march the national aerospace 
plane still on the drawing boards is favored by 70 percent up 
from 57 percent last year 
on the 20th anniversary last july of mans first landing on the 
moon bush outlined a goal of returning to the moon and sending 
manned expeditions to mars early in the next century only 64 
percent of the poll respondents favored the lunar proposal and only 
62 percent favored going to mars 
while 85 percent of the respondents believe it is important that 
the united states take the lead in developing new technologies for 
those programs and for monitoring the environment only 56 percent 
agreed that the government should spend whatever is necessary 
to maintain its position of leadership 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

