<TEXT>
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers 
throughout the country 
march 9 
statesman journal salem ore on the bush transportation plan 
when candidate george bush said read my lips no new 
taxes we didnt know exactly what he meant as president george 
bush he has spelled it out hell pass federal duties on to local 
governments and let them pay the bill and raise the taxes 
thats what he and congress already have done with education and 
health care and its what he proposes in his new moving america 
into the 21st century plan for our transportation system 
the federal government would continue paying the costs for 
interstate and many major highways but it would give states and 
local governments the bill for building and maintaining millions of 
miles of other highways and it would impose extensive user fees 
for motorists truckers air travelers and mass transit customers 
this is a tax increase by another name its a tax increase that 
local governments cannot pay and probably should not have to pay 
for a transportation system that is national in scope 
at the least washington should deal with us honestly if our 
crumbling and clogged highways are a national problem remedy it 
with a national program and admit that federal taxes must be 
increased or that other programs must be cut back to save the 
money 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 11 
the providence ri journalbulletin on the bush 
transportation plan 
as many travelers know parts of americas transportation 
network have fallen on hard times many highways and bridges are 
crumbling under heavy traffic major airports are choked with 
congestion passenger rail service is scattered and spotty and 
urban mass transit is often a joke 
the bush administration has dug bravely into this thicket of 
problems its new transportation policy represents a sharp 
departure from past practice it seeks essentially to shrink the 
federal role in everything from highway maintenance to mass transit 
operations and to transfer many costs to state and local 
governments 
in a nation the size of the united states transportation is a 
national concern deserving national treatment it is by no means 
assured that transferring large pieces of this responsibility to 
local governments is the best way to restore our battered system to 
health 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 13 
los angeles times on the rostenkowski deficit reduction plan 
for most americans the national debt is as abstract as the 
numbers that measure it currently about 3000000000000 as in 
trillion 
getting washington to focus again on the debt is only one reason 
to cheer rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of the house ways 
and means committe for his bold plan to slash the federal budget 
deficit 
the more than 150 billion a year that vanishes into interest 
payments means that there is much less money in circulation for 
private investment and in turn economic expansion and job 
creation this debt is of increasing consequence as the economy 
slows down because it severely cuts the nations ability to bail 
itself out of a severe recession 
rostenkowskis plan would not wipe out the national debt but 
would keep it from growing after 1994 
where would the money come from a oneyear freeze on 
costofliving increases in all federal programs would cut the 
deficit by 9 percent the first year higher taxes on oil tobacco 
alcohol and industrial pollutants would cut it another 20 billion 
cutting the pentagon budget by 3 percent a year would convert 
another 10 billion from red ink to black families with incomes 
above 185000 a year who now pay income taxes as a 28 percent 
rate would pay the same 33 percent that families with smaller 
incomes pay 
the white house and some republican leaders in congress 
resisted any temptation to attack the plan that plus renewed 
attention to the deficit is an improvement over recent behavior on 
all sides 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 10 
kennebec journal augusta maine on clean air legislation 
twenty years after the clean air act was first passed the 
senate majority leader george mitchell has clinched a deal to 
overhaul and strengthen it 
following 12 days of closeddoor meetings mitchell unveiled a 
compromise which the bush administration supports business is 
grumbling about and some environmental groups are wild about in 
the most purple prose mitchell is said to have gutted the bill 
thats nonsense mitchell knows that after a decade of inaction 
begun with the inauguration of ronald trees cause pollution 
reagan the nation has got to get a new clean air bill on the books 
to be sure there are disappointments pollution reduction 
techniques for cars and trucks contributing perhaps half of all 
ozone pollution are highly developed but the technology has not 
been used sufficiently thanks largely to reagan this time out 
bushs proposal for alternative fuel vehicles was cut as were the 
most stringent tailpipe standards 
on the other hand the acid rainfighting measures cracking 
down on high sulfur coal burning in the midwest are mostly intact 
the most punitive sanctions for cities exceeding federal pollution 
standards shutting down all development arent going to be used 
anyway so their loss is mostly symbolic 
all in all mitchell has done well any comparison with the 
clean air acts of 1970 and 1990 shows some major improvements long 
overdue mitchells critics ought to remember that the deadlock of 
reagan years where a president stubbornly refused to acknowledge 
scientific reality is unlikely to recur if this doesnt work the 
law can be changed again but its still a big step forward the 
first in a long long time 
</TEXT>
