march 7 
the news and courier charleston sc on the soviet union 
mikhail gorbachev never has been unwilling to take the plunge 
to a market economy principally because of his desire to seek 
marxistleninist answers to the countrys ills 
but the recent explosions of ethnic and regional animosities in 
azerbaijan armenia and turkistan and the growing separatist 
movements in the baltic republics of estonia latvia and lithuania 
have served only to make gorbachev even more reluctant to bite 
the bullet and embrace market solutions 
as a result shortages of every conceivable item from food to 
fuel have become more severe there are simply too many rubles 
chasing too few goods at fixed artificial prices and the result is 
a populace that is hungry angry and increasingly alienated by 
gorbachevs promise to cleave to the leninist path 
radical soviet politician boris yeltsin as his showings in 
the last three elections have demonstrated has proved a master at 
tapping the deep undercurrent of unrest in the soviet union this 
is the last chance for the party he told a cheering crowd in 
moscow recently this is also gorbachevs last chance either he 
acts or he loses us 
tough words but yeltsin has demonstrated that he has more 
than enough popular muscle to back them up 
</TEXT>
