<TEXT>
a 1987 amendment to the maine 
constitution that says the right to bear arms shall never be 
questioned does not mean felons have the right to own guns the 
states highest court ruled today 
plainly the people of maine who voted for the amendment never 
intended that an inmate at maine state prison or a patient in a 
mental hospital would have an absolute right to bear a firearm 
the unanimous maine supreme judicial court said 
the justices struck down a ruling from a superior court judge 
who said last year that the amendment did not prohibit a 
nonviolent habitual traffic offender edward brown from owning a 
gun 
this is a victory for common sense state attorney general 
james e tierney said in augusta the supreme court has avoided a 
hypertechnical reading of the statute 
browns lawyer daniel bates was out of town and not 
immediately available for comment a secretary said 
the amendment approved by voters said every citizen has a 
right to keep and bear arms and this right shall never be 
questioned it struck out the words for the common defense 
from the original righttobeararms provision 
prior to the 1987 amendment the maine constitution afforded no 
absolute right to keep and bear arms and we now hold that no 
absolute right was created by the amendment todays ruling said 
the justices said the evident purpose of the amendment was merely 
to transform a collective right to bear arms into an individual 
right and nothing more 
the justices also said the amendment did not invalidate a state 
law prohibiting gun possession by felons 
one who has committed any felony has displayed a degree of 
lawlessness that makes it entirely reasonable for the legislature 
concerned for the safety of the public it represents to want to 
keep firearms out of the hands of such a person the justices 
said 
the case had fostered an unusual alliance among the national 
rifle association the national center to prevent handgun violence 
the sportsmans alliance of maine and the maine chiefs of police 
association all the groups supported the state attorney generals 
appeal of the lower court ruling 
the amendment was prompted by a 1986 maine supreme court ruling 
that upheld the illegal possession of firearms conviction of a 
felon who had argued that the constitution guaranteed his right to 
bear arms 
in that ruling the justices found that the constitution 
protected the right to bear arms only for the common defense 
</TEXT>
