business inventories resumed their slow growth 
in january after a onemonth decline the government reported 
wednesday and analysts said the 02 percent gain confirms the 
sluggishness in the manufacturing economy 
the commerce department said inventories totaled a seasonally 
adjusted 7959 billion including a steep 07 percent jump in 
manufacturing backlogs 
inventories as a whole fell 04 percent in december the first 
drop since a 01 percent decline in october 1988 and the largest 
since a 06 percent fall in december 1986 the december drop was 
originally reported to be 02 percent 
the january report is confirming what we already know that 
the area of manufacturing is beginning to slow said economist 
thomas runiewicz of the wefa group in bala cynwyd pa 
were starting to see rises in paper and chemicals and a lot 
of basic commodities that are used daily throughout the whole 
manufacturing industry he said what were seeing is that as 
the industry slows down the demand for commodities slows down 
the commerce department also reported a 03 percent increase in 
business sales to a seasonally adjusted 532 billion in january 
after falling a revised 02 percent in december december sales 
first were reported unchanged from november 
the january report resulted in a 152 ratio of inventories to 
sales the same as december but down slightly from a 153 ratio in 
both october and november the ratio means that it would take 152 
months to exhaust inventories at the january pace 
inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as 
output exceeds demand if they were to pile up excessively it 
could mean cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs possibly 
leading to a recession 
but runiewicz said current inventory levels are not indicative 
of negative economic growth 
if anything when comparing what weve experienced in previous 
recessions weve been able to maintain or get more of a grip on 
inventories he said previous recessions were accompanied by 
some inventories becoming out of control 
retail backlogs fell 06 percent in january while sales rose 
28 percent automobile inventories dropped 36 percent as auto 
manufacturers temporarily laid off thousands of workers during the 
month to trim the number of motor vehicles stuck on backlots 
but while manufacturing inventories grew 07 percent sales 
dropped 19 percent 
wholesalers inventories advanced 02 percent while their sales 
gained 14 percent 
