<TEXT>
three weeks ago a mongolian opposition leader 
predicted that the pace of political change in ulan bator would be 
faster than in moscow 
the events of the past week have proved sanjaasuren zorig right 
the leadership has bowed to opposition demands for sweeping 
political changes and those who just a few weeks ago talked about 
the ideal government and economy for mongolia must now find ways to 
realize those dreams 
on monday the communist party politburo decided to abolish its 
constitutional guarantee on power replace the politburo and party 
general secretary jambyn batmonh hold early legislative elections 
and write a new constitution 
the central committee on thursday approved ending the 
66yearold guarantee on power chose a reformer to lead the party 
and installed its youngest politburo in years 
these changes come less than three months after mongolias first 
opposition group the mongolian democratic union headed by zorig 
came on the scene staging peaceful rallies urging political reform 
since then a halfdozen other political groups have emerged 
and three political parties have formed the latest tuesday 
the groups have joined together to urge faster sweeping 
political reform even though they disagree on what type of 
government and economy would be best for mongolia a nation of 19 
million 
in late february zorig sat beneath a portrait of karl marx in a 
classroom at the mongolian state university in the capital ulan 
bator he told a small group of reporters what he envisions for 
mongolias future 
the most important thing to be carried out is political 
changes the main methods to carry out this political construction 
is first to create a multiparty system introduce a parliamentary 
system and have presidential rule he said 
also to give political freedom to the people 
zorig a 27yearold postgraduate student of scientific 
communism and a former university lecturer envisaged a collective 
not stateowned economy 
zorig said he wanted to turn this creditfed economy into an 
independent economy mongolia has been economically dependent on 
the soviet union for decades and western economists put the debt 
at close to 6 billion 
land would be leased for cultivation and there would be no 
limits on the number of privately owned cattle in this nomadic 
society where 70 percent of the population still are herdsmen 
enterprises would be decentralized and leased to workers and those 
operating at a loss would be shut down 
the main goal is that those who are working should taste the 
real fruits of their work zorig said 
if the current leadership steps down zorig said a coalition 
government probably would be formed 
surely we will be members of that he said even in this 
year the mongolian democratic party will be member of parliament 
