<TEXT>
an uninsured 140 million 
communications satellite failed to separate from its launch rocket 
wednesday and orbited uselessly around earth launch officials said 
efforts were under way to separate the satellite and rocket with 
signals from ground stations while it is attached to the big titan 
3 that boosted it into orbit the satellite cannot be fired into 
the 22300milehigh orbit at which it must operate 
initial review of data suggest separation did not occur 
martin marietta corp said in a onesentence statement 
martin marietta which conducted the launch earlier reported 
that the satellite had separated although the spacecraft failed to 
send any signals back to earth following the 652 am est launch 
if the satellite were doomed it would represent a total 270 
million loss including the cost of the rocket and launch 
the satellite was intended to transmit up to 120000 telephone 
calls simultaneously for several companies and three television 
channels for more than 13 years it was to replace two older 
satellites over the atlantic 
don oneal a spokesman for hughes aircraft co which built the 
satellite earlier said it could be days before the satellite was 
declared a failure 
its not a failure until we can confirm some things here 
said martin marietta spokeswoman judy stowell an investigation 
needs to occur 
the 5ton satellite nearly four stories tall with its antennas 
and solar panels deployed was boosted into orbit by titan 3 the 
most powerful us commercial rocket the rocket blasted off into a 
cloudy sky from the cape canaveral air force station 
launch commentator bob gordon a spokesman for martin marietta 
reported 28 minutes after launch that it had separated from the 
rocket as scheduled a few minutes later he said the separation 
had not been confirmed 
at 837 am gordon announced we have just received 
confirmation of deployment the separation occurred 25 minutes 
after launch he said 
edward m browne president of martin marietta commercial titan 
inc said at a late morning news conference that despite the lack 
of a signal it looks like the rocket performed as it was 
supposed to 
however no data was received from the satellite when it was 
scheduled to pass over a tracking station on hawaii 
hughes earlier said it was not clear whether an onboard rocket 
motor fired to send the satellite into a higher orbit something 
that could not have happened had the orbiter not separated from the 
rocket the motor normally would have fired before the satellite 
sent its first signals back to earth 
the us space command in colorado which tracks objects in 
space said it was asked by martin marietta to locate the satellite 
we are performing our normal tracking function we know where 
it is said maj thomas niemann a command spokesman 
frederick ormsby spacecraft mission director for the 
international telecommunications satellite organization or 
intelsat said the notforprofit international consortium had not 
insured the satellite insuring satellites is prohibitively high 
especially since last months explosion of an ariane rocket 
the unmanned ariane rocket carrying two japanese communications 
satellites blew apart over the atlantic shortly after taking off 
from kourou french guiana 
the intelsat vi that took off wednesday was the fourth 
commercial launch of a payload to orbit by an american company 
the satellite was scheduled to reach final orbit 22300 miles 
above earth on sunday and then undergo tests before being placed 
in service in late may 
the first intelsat vi launched october by the european space 
agencys ariane rocket is being tested in orbit and will be placed 
in service april 7 
wednesdays launch was the 44th for intelsat a washington 
dcbased commercial cooperative of 118 member nations the 
cooperative owns and operates a global communications satellite 
system used by more than 170 countries the first intelsat 
communications satellite was launched 25 years ago next month 
