<TEXT>
tucked away near the end of the 
administrations 129page transportation policy is a brief and 
general pledge to work for oil conservation a faint echo of the 
energy crisis that dominated the national agenda not so long ago 
in the era of the oil embargo of gasoline lines and rocketing 
prices that spiraled inflation energy was a major problem for two 
presidents and a dominant political issue during much of the 1970s 
now it is backofthebook stuff despite increasing us dependence 
on imported oil 
imports an embargo and a cut in foreign oil supplies were 
components of the energy crises that confronted richard m nixon 
and beset jimmy carter they advocated policies to make sure it 
couldnt happen again 
but it could 
oil imports in january were the highest in 12 years imports 
have been rising domestic oil production falling prices are down 
which makes foreign oil less expensive than the alternatives but 
it certainly isnt inexpensive oil imports account for about 50 
billion of the persistent us trade deficit 
according to the american petroleum institute imported oil 
accounted for 54 percent of us consumption in january a record 
high cia director william webster has told congress that reliance 
on persian gulf oil is likely to increase markedly over the next 
several years 
nixon launched project independence seeking to end us 
dependence on foreign energy sources after the arab oil embargo it 
didnt happen carter said in 1977 the nation should declare the 
moral equivalent of war to master its energy problems carter later 
was taunted with his programs acronym meow parts of his program 
were shelved as some others expired they were not renewed 
the crises eased foreign oil became plentiful and relatively 
cheap and ronald reagans administration pushed the whole issue 
far down the agenda slashing the energy conservation budget and 
proposing unsuccessfully that congress eliminate the department 
of energy 
now bushs department of energy is at work on a new national 
energy strategy with the initial version due next month and the 
final report before the end of the year 
it will have to be a companion piece to the transportation 
policy statement which observes 
transportation accounts for more than a quarter of total 
national energy consumption and close to twothirds of the 
petroleum used in the united states each year 
it goes on to say that conservation and more efficient motor 
vehicles have led to significant energy savings in the past two 
decades and that there is more to come 
the transportation policy pledges to foster development and 
use of more fuelefficient vehicles and transportation 
operations there are no specific recommendations on the 
politically and economically sensitive issue of future fuel economy 
standards to be required of us automobile manufacturers 
the requirements were relaxed during reagans second term 
secretary of transportation samuel k skinner reinstated them for 
the 1990 model year requiring that cars produced by each us 
manufacturer get an average 275 miles per gallon of gas congress 
may act later this year on amendments to the fuel economy rules set 
after the 19731974 arab oil embargo 
noting that some forms of travel are more energyefficient than 
others in meeting the same needs the transportation policy says 
that mass transit and inter city rail service can serve as 
fuelsaving alternatives to the private automobile in heavily 
populated areas 
it also proposes to end operating subsidies and reduce other 
federal spending for mass transit and rail passenger service so 
that passengers cities and states will pick up the cost 
the theory is that those are local and regional not national 
facilities and so should be paid for locally and regionally that 
may not mesh with a transportation strategy in which conserving oil 
is a national aim 
but then theres no crisis now 
</TEXT>
