<TEXT>
the safety measures set up in prince 
william sound since the wreck of the exxon valdez are impressive 
oil skimmers lie waiting in remote bays and powerful tugs trail 
every tanker leaving port 
the hostile glare of publicity forced the improvements in 
alaska but critics say the oil industry has a long way to go 
toward preventing and cleaning up spills elsewhere in the nation 
what oil companies do best is discover produce ship and 
market oil cleaning spills is not their bag said walt parker 
chairman of an alaska state task force that studied the valdez 
spill theyll do as much as they have to and no more 
the us house has passed a bill that would allow states to 
adopt stricter spill liability laws than the federal government and 
require double hulls on all tankers in us waters 
a conference committee now is trying to reconcile differences 
with a weaker senate bill which calls for more study on double 
hulls and leaves the final decision up to the secretary of 
transportation 
legislatures in nearly every seaboard state are considering 
proposals to increase tanker and oil barge safety or improve spill 
cleanup capabilities 
large spills are something we face in all our port areas 
said sarah chasis attorney for the natural resources defense 
council a new yorkbased environmental group there will always 
be a certain number of oil spills but many measures can be taken 
to reduce their likelihood 
oil companies hoped to head off some of the legislative furor 
last june by announcing a 250 million fiveyear plan to create a 
nationwide network of spillresponse teams but it has stalled as 
the companies watch what action congress and the states take 
the public outrage over the exxon valdez accident last march 24 
has been kept alive by a string of messy fuel spills around the 
country 
in the past year at least 81 spills of more than 5000 gallons 
occurred in the united states said spill expert richard golob of 
cambridge mass 
the most significant ones according to his newsletter golobs 
oil pollution bulletin 
june 23 the greek tanker world prodigy hit a reef off rhode 
island spilling 420000 gallons of heating oil the same day a 
barge collided with a tanker in texas spilling 252000 gallons of 
slurry oil into the houston ship channel the next day a uruguayan 
tanker ran aground in the delaware river spilling 300000 gallons 
of fuel oil 
jan 1 an underwater pipeline running from an exxon refinery 
ruptured spilling 567000 gallons of heating oil into arthur kill 
a busy industrial waterway between new jersey and new yorks staten 
island 
feb 7 the american trader chartered by british petroleum 
was gored by its own anchor and spilled nearly 400000 gallons of 
alaskan crude oil off huntington beach in southern california 
feb 28march 6 three accidents within a week leaked a total 
of 160000 gallons of crude fuel and heating oil into new jerseys 
arthur kill and adjoining kill van kull 
except for the massive exxon valdez spill which totaled about 
108 million gallons the accidents were business as usual for the 
oil transportation industry golob said 
professionals in the oilpollution field know that oil spills 
take place on a regular basis he said the main difference 
this year is the extensive media coverage of oil spills in 1988 a 
spill of 1 million gallons might have occupied a oneinch story in 
the new york times in 1989 a spill that large would have taken 
over half the page 
as oil from the american trader washed up on southern california 
beaches stores sold tshirts proclaiming crude is rude dude 
and campaigning politicians held so many shoreside press 
conferences that the mayor of huntington beach asked for advance 
notice so they wouldnt interfere with cleanup efforts 
an oilspill measure previously given little chance of passage 
was put on the fast track in the california assembly it would 
tighten control of tanker traffic and create a 500 million cleanup 
fund from a 50centabarrel tax on crude oil brought into the 
state 
other states considering strengthened controls include 
louisiana where state wildlife officials want double hulls on all 
tankers using state waters and rhode island where a bill 
introduced with the state attorney generals blessing would make 
oil shippers assume unlimited liability for damages caused by 
spills even if no negligence is proved 
environmentalists are cheered by the explosion of legislative 
action especially the us house proposal for doublehulled 
tankers a requirement repeatedly defeated by the oil industry for 
nearly 20 years 
the oil industry argues that double hulls could make ships more 
unstable in major accidents and says the cost of building new 
tankers or retrofitting old ones would be high only 10 percent of 
the worlds fleet of 3200 large tankers have double hulls or 
double bottoms said american petroleum institute spokesman bill 
taylor 
but chasis the attorney for the environmental group said 
studies have shown double hulls or bottoms would prevent or greatly 
limit most spills 
the cost of one major oil spill like the exxon valdez which 
is 2 billion and mounting could pay for the increased cost of 
building 100 or more tankers with double hulls she said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david foster is the ap northwest regional 
reporter based in seattle 
