<TEXT>
the wreck of the exxon valdez forced more 
scrutiny and higher costs on alaskas oil industry and may have 
delayed for years the exploration for new oil in the states vast 
arctic wilderness 
in the six weeks from the tanker disaster to the legislatures 
mandated adjournment lawmakers raised industry taxes and spill 
fines strengthened plans for spill prevention and cleanup and set 
up an independent investigatory commission 
this year even as the reform momentum slows they are 
considering more spill bills including a package by gov steve 
cowper that would allow the state to inspect tankers and increase 
liability requirements for companies transporting or storing oil 
such enthusiasm for reining in alaskas largest and most 
lucrative industry would have been inconceivable before march 24 
1989 the day of the big spill 
alaska depends on oil like no other state deriving about 85 
percent of its revenues from oil taxes and royalties its 531000 
residents pay no state sales or income taxes yet the state leads 
the nation in percapita spending 
at the same time the thick flow of crude has helped the state 
amass a 105 billion savings account its earnings yield an annual 
dividend to every alaskan last years was 873 
for a decade we had seen nothing but the up side which was 
state revenues with no pain to the public said senate president 
tim kelly a republican what we saw from the exxon valdez was 
the down side of the oil business 
the oil stains and smears left on the treasured landscape of 
prince william sound angered alaskans who felt betrayed by their 
favored industry and by their legislators no one was spared the 
fingerpointing 
we got slapped around said house speaker sam cotten a 
democrat 
so did the industry 
it was almost the oil industry vs the state of alaska said 
bill webb general manager of the prooil alaska support industry 
alliance thats a dangerous position for a state to be in with 
its largest industry 
the emotion in which eight spill bills were swiftly passed last 
spring has dissipated but its an election year and environmental 
protection remains a priority legislators predict passage of three 
or four more oilrelated bills by may 
we were the legislature on watch when this thing happened 
cotten said so its really up to us to get it all done 
but some say much remains to be done 
sue libenson executive director of the alaska center for the 
environment said the states response has been overrated last 
years spill bills were stopgap measures that dealt only with 
the immediate disaster she said 
we didnt see anything that would really prevent future 
spills she said we have yet to create any new policies to give 
real longterm incentives to polluters not to pollute 
and lawmakers with more time to reflect no longer are rushing 
to vote against the oil industry 
the lynchmob mentality has left the legislature and cooler 
