minority leader 
that is welcome news for jim palmer a spokesman for bp 
exploration alaska inc an arm of giant british petroleum 
last year if any piece of legislation had oil spill on it 
it was automatically assumed correct and needed without as much 
scrutiny as normally is given palmer said this year that has 
changed all different views on the thing are being heard 
including ours 
legislators also worry about the spills effect on oil 
exploration the disaster held up legislation in congress that 
would have opened the arctic national wildlife refuge for 
exploration 
the huge fields at nearby prudhoe bay supply about 25 percent of 
the nations domestic oil but production is declining the best 
hope to maintain production and keep revenues flowing may be the 
wildlife refuge known to alaskans by its acronym anwr 
support for opening the refuge to exploration remains strong in 
alaska despite the exxon valdez spill 
the majority of the legislature and the majority of alaskans 
continue to support the safe and orderly development of anwr 
said kelly the senate president on the national level the 
spill probably held it back a year or two 
alaskas sole congressman republican don young is optimistic 
congress eventually will act on the refuge 
the nation needs anwr opened because were importing over 50 
percent of our oil a position that is much more precarious than 
during the 1973 oil embargo when the united states imported 36 
percent of its oil young said 
but the wreck of the exxon valdez gave environmentalists a new 
weapon against opening the refuge 
its made everyone sit up and say gee is it really worth 
the risk are the oil industrys assurances that everything will be 
fine something that we can rely on said mike wenig attorney 
for the environmental group trustees of alaska 
as the spill has focused attention on alaskas oil dependence 
the state has continued efforts to diversify its economy exports 
of seafood timber and minerals were up sharply last year and 
anchorage got a boost when federal express chose the city as its 
international cargo hub 
but economic diversification will be tough to achieve in this 
remote state 
were just not close enough to the marketplaces to compete in 
software high technology or something of that nature kelly 
said so with the exception of tourism in the foreseeable 
decades we are going to be a resourcedevelopment state 
and the most profitable resource in alaska remains oil 
nobody wants to get out of the oil business in alaska kelly 
said its just too lucrative 
