said charles cook author of a washingtonbased political 
newsletter they can work quietly and its effective but when 
they go too far its going to hurt them 
a state senate race in california last fall is cited as one 
example 
democrat lucy killea running in a special election was barred 
from taking communion because of her support for abortion rights 
her subsequent victory was widely credited to the attention and 
sympathy generated by the ban imposed by bishop leo maher of san 
diego 
catholics for free choice a private group that supports 
abortion rights said it knows of cases where catholic public 
officeholders or candidates have been pressured by church leaders 
over the abortion issue in at least eight states frances kissling 
president of the group cited cases in montana connecticut 
pennsylvania alaska washington new york new jersey and 
california 
she said killea is the only known case where a catholic 
politician has been denied communion because of abortion views but 
others she said have felt more subtle threats 
theyre afraid afraid theyre going to get up one morning 
and be refused communion afraid theyre going to be embarrassed by 
church officials she said 
the efforts have not not changed minds on the issue kissling 
contends but have caused some officials to shrink from leadership 
roles such as sponsoring legislation 
although kissling worries about a chilling effect some 
political leaders say they see no evidence that church activity is 
hurting the abortionrights cause 
it can be a powerful tool but i think its backfiring said 
kate michelman head of the national abortion rights action league 
theres a great sensitivity in this country to separation of 
church and state 
the national right to life committee the leading antiabortion 
lobbying group works with church groups but distances itself from 
the actions of religious leaders 
we just dont really get involved in religious issues said 
spokeswoman nancy myers 
the complaints about religious meddling in the politics of 
abortion come as catholic leaders appear to be asserting themselves 
more on public policy issues said the rev richard neuhaus a 
lutheran who is director of the institute on religion and public 
life in new york 
i think there is a new consensus among the bishops that there 
is a new level of agreement and urgency in making the churchs 
teachings credible with public officeholders he said 
catholic bishops approved a resolution last november that put a 
priority on lobbying against abortion rights it urged public 
officials especially catholics to advance these goals in 
recognition of their moral responsibility 
cardinal john oconnor chairman of the bishops committee for 
prolife activities wrote each member of congress this month to 
state opposition to a bill that would write the supreme courts 
abortion guarantees into federal law he sent each congressman a 
picture of an 18weekold fetus to illustrate the insanity of our 
nations current policy sanctioning abortion on demand 
kissling sees evidence catholic leaders are pursuing an 
overall strategy to pressure officeholders that goes beyond mere 
lobbying an activity she does not question 
but bob wonderly a spokesman for the us catholic conference 
the public policy and lobbying arm of the church said there was no 
agreement to sanction churchgoers whose public actions are at odds 
with the church on abortion 
each bishop is doing what he feels is necessary to fulfill his 
ministry wonderly said 
</TEXT>
