<TEXT>
a bill giving the securities and exchange 
commission authority to curb program trading in stock market 
emergencies has moved a step closer to law despite objections from 
the treasury department 
the securities markets stabilization act was approved 
unanimously on a voice vote tuesday by the house energy and 
commerce committee 
the bill would allow the sec to limit program trading and other 
activities during periods of extraordinary market volatility 
but the scope of that power was narrowed in an amendment to the 
bill which now goes to the full house for approval 
the treasury department made public a letter from undersecretary 
robert r glauber to the committee opposing a program trading 
restriction stating the department believed the reform bill was 
too important to be jeopardized by a controversial and 
unnecessary provision to shut down program trading 
meanwhile a member of the panel said he plans to introduce 
legislation with a member of the house agriculture committee to 
unify jurisdiction for hybrid financial instruments under one 
agency 
the sec which regulates securities and the commodity futures 
trading commission which oversees the futures markets have been 
waging a turf battle over new financial products tha fall in the 
middle 
often called hybrids they have characteristics of both 
securities and futures a federal appeals court ruled last year 
that securities with any aspect of a futures contract should come 
under the cftcs jurisdiction prompting the sec and the exchanges 
it regulates to seek reform 
rep dennis e eckart dohio said he and rep dan glickman 
dkan would introduce comprehensive institutional reform 
between the sec and the cftc to give jursdiction for all these 
hybrid instruments to one agency 
glickman said said he didnt want to give the jurisdiction to 
either the sec or cftc but sought to establish a new federal 
regulatory body to oversee futures options securities and related 
instruments 
he said the proposed legislation was still in the formative 
stages and a long way from being introduced 
until we see something of a concrete nature we really cant 
comment it would be premature said cftc spokesman david gary 
he added we continue to support the concept of exclusive 
jurisdiction 
the proposed bill with the program trading reforms was an 
outgrowth of the 1987 stock market crash it also would require 
securities firms to keep and supply information to federal 
regulators about the financial health of their parent holding 
companies 
a similar market reform bill but without a program trading 
provision is pending before the senate 
the program trading amendment would limit sec control powers to 
activities previously determined to cause or contribute to 
extraordinary volatility that is sharp rises and drops in stock 
prices such a determination would be made through the secs often 
time consuming rulemaking procedure of public hearings comment 
letter and staff review 
the change satisfied rep norman lent rny whose objections 
to antiprogram trading language in a previous version of the bill 
prevented its quick approval by the full committee last fall 
at that time he and other members of the telecommunications and 
finance subcommittee argued that language introduced by rep 
edward j markey dmass the subcommittee chairman was vague and 
ambiguous 
originally markey wanted to limit activity that was 
disruptive abusive or manipulative 
markey said the new language was worked out after three months 
of negotiations among committee democrats and republicans the sec 
and the securities industry 
i cant say im thrilled with the version we have before us 
but its a long way from the original version said lent 
the bill also empowers the sec to obtain information and monitor 
large securities transactions and to halt trading with the 
presidents assent during market emergencies 
</TEXT>
