<DOCNO> AP900314-0174 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
its the year of the horse but the 
turtle might be a more fitting symbol for chinas economy as it 
enters the 1990s with millions of factories shutting down and 
workers idled 
boomtown china with its ubiquitous construction cranes and 
conspicuous consumption has given way to a cashstarved economy 
pushed to the brink of recession by a government determined to curb 
inflation 
inflation is falling retail prices were up about 7 percent by 
yearend about a third of the official inflation rate for the 
previous two years 
but the process of curbing it has brought new problems equally 
troubling the government which showed through its violent 
suppression of a prodemocracy movement nearly a year ago that it 
values stability above all 
unemployment and indebtedness have grown sharply and 
productivity has fallen the 1980s entrepreneurial spirit has 
subsided replaced by renewed emphasis on central planning and 
political correctness 
the government began its attack on inflation in late 1988 by 
ordering sharp cuts in construction official spending and loans 
but the full impact hit in the last quarter of 1989 when 
industrial output grew at an annual rate of less than 1 percent 
vs nearly 21 percent for all of 1988 
in a series of emergency moves the government loaned state 
companies nearly 27 billion at the end of the year and ordered 
factories to recall laidoff workers even if they had nothing to do 
this month premier li peng hinted at an early end to the 
retrenchment which was to have lasted three years when he called 
for development to be brought back to a reasonable pace more 
significant economic shifts may be disclosed at the upcoming 
national peoples congress session 
they were running into a recession but they pulled up at the 
last minute said a western economic analyst speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
she said local governments also cushioned the shock by loaning 
money to the worsthit companies and helping others merge or 
restructure 
there seems to be a lot of flexibility in the system to create 
safety nets she said 
but others believe restarting the engine will not be that easy 
before people were on a roll they were willing to say lets 
do it it took 10 years for people to forget that making 
decisions could be risky said a western diplomat now theyve 
been reminded and everyone wants to wait for the central 
governments sayso 
so far the economic slowdown is less apparent in the shops 
which remain full than in the warehouses 
televisions refrigerators electric fans bicycles rugs and 
dozens of other products in high demand a year ago are piling up in 
storehouses as consumers heed the governments call to spend less 
and save more 
the result has been to idle millions of workers making the 
nolongerpopular items in january china made 40 percent fewer 
color tvs than in january 1989 and about half as many cars washing 
machines and refrigerators state statistics show 
government officials say privately that unemployment among urban 
workers is 4 percent and growing but the figure would be much 
higher if it includd the millions who spend their days doing 
unproductive work cleaning workshops studying political 
documents playing cards 
rural authorities have organized tree planting and water 
conservancy projects to occupy the millions of peasants sent home 
from city construction teams or laid off from tiny rural factories 
that were the first casualties of the austerity 
workers with jobs also have felt pinched wages have failed to 
pace even the reduced inflation 
the foreign employment service corp in shanghai which supplies 
personnel for foreign employers stopped paying wages for months a 
shoe factory in shanghai paid its workers in shoes which they 
tried to hawk on the main shopping street 
angry workers have sought permission to demonstrate in several 
cities chinese sources say and unconfirmed reports describe 
actual marches in the northeast chinas heavyindustry heartland 
authorities deny the reports 
they acknowledge however that many factories are in trouble 
nationwide companies owe each other a total of 21 billion because 
cashpoor banks wont release funds 
yao fugen president of the shanghai no 1 sewing machine 
factory doesnt ship any machines now unless hes paid first 
denied credit by banks he also borrowed more than 3 million from 
customers swapped sewing machines for pig iron and began 
testmanufacturing fishing rods as a hedge against the soft sewing 
machine market 
the government says manufacturers who show ingenuity will 
survive and inefficient ones will fail ultimately benefiting the 
economy 
in practice the survivors are stateowned factories notorious 
for inefficiency while millions of private collective and other 
nonstate factories have closed banks refuse them loans and they 
find it harder than ever to get raw materials because the 
government has recentralized distribution 
authorities are trying to improve productivity at the state 
factories by stepping up marxist education among the workers and 
reviving the past art of elevating labor heros 
but at three large state factories in shanghai the industrial 
heart of china communist party secretaries said marxist study was 
mainly limited to party members 
western analysts agree that action was needed to cool inflation 
but they worry the government will hit the pump again without 
correcting any basic problems such as irrational prices and taxes 
a western diplomat predicted they may go through all this 
pain with nothing to show for it 
