<TEXT>
every year 20yearold sun lili travels 
three days by bus and train to a factory near canton to buy cartons 
of brightly colored hair trinkets and plastic jewelry 
she hauls them back to wenzhou a port city midway up the 
chinese coast and resells them from her own private stall 
not many women her age in china have that much spunk but not 
many young women earn 10000 yuan or more than 2100 a year either 
about five times the average workers wage 
in wenzhou however sun is far from extraordinary private 
business is the citys lifeblood and has been for generations to 
hear residents talk 
since the song dynasty wenzhou has had a commodity economy 
said ma jinlong referring to the 10th century rulers of china ma 
is deputy director of the city systems restructuring commission 
another oddity not many cities as small and remote as wenzhou 
have thinktanks to encourage private and other nonstate 
enterprise 
as a result while private factories account for less than 5 
percent of the nationwide industrial output in wenzhou they 
produce more than 32 percent most of the shops and restaurants are 
private and tens of thousands of wenzhou residents hit the road 
each year as traveling salesmen 
wenzhou 250 miles south of shanghai seems to lack the 
requirements of a commercial center it has no airport although 
one is nearing completion and no rail link 
visitors endure a 24hour ferry ride from shanghai or 10hour 
drive from hangzhou to the northwest 
youve heard of capitalist tails asked a visiting 
shanghai woman that was what the radical leftists during the 
196676 cultural revolution called anything that smacked of 
capitalism well wenzhou was a capitalist tail 
during the mid1980s the city briefly became the tail that 
wagged the dog as top officials and delegates from around china 
visited to observe the wenzhou model for prosperity 
encouraging householdbased small businesses 
thenpremier and later communist party secretary zhao ziyang a 
leading proponent of market reforms visited in 1985 but zhao was 
ousted last june accused of embracing dangerous liberalism 
his successor as party chief jiang zemin has made a point of 
visiting major state factories and revolutionary war bases 
with the dual aim of curbing inflation and reviving marxist 
spirit the central government has cut off loans and supplies to 
nonstate enterprises it also has ordered deep cuts in spending 
and construction pushing the national economy almost into 
recession 
wenzhou again is under a shadow authorities have begun policing 
its private businessmen more closely for tax evasion and smuggling 
and some have been arrested or forced to close 
late last year a wenzhou man who ran a private credit union was 
executed he apparently misused funds to build and furnish his 
home but official reports of the case broadly criticized all 
private credit unions as speculative undertakings meant for 
reaping windfall profits 
