<TEXT>
faint murmurs rise from the floor a 
voice intones now start trading 
figures flash on an electronic board us dollars are selling 
for 591 yuan the previous days closing price and 12 yuan over 
the official exchange rate 
sellers are hawking 54 million and buyers want 53 million a 
bank trims its sales offer and the figures match the price stays 
unchanged 
it took two minutes within an hour all the transactions have 
been processed and the clients have left the shanghai currency 
exchange 
market employees relax with a noisy game of pingpong on a table 
in front of the big board housed in an imposing former bank from 
the precommunist days when shanghai was an asian financial center 
our market is elementary one could even say primitive said 
qiu jirong a young worker at the shanghai foreign exchange 
transaction center 
nonetheless it is the most sophisticated tool china has for 
matching up chinese and foreign companies that need dollars with 
those that have dollars and need the local currency renminbi a 
yuan is the basic unit of renminbi 
the renminbi like most socialist countries currencies is not 
convertible on world markets and chinese banks hoard hard 
currencies because they are needed to buy foreign goods before 
china opened its first currency exchange markets in 1986 most 
foreign companies that earned renminbi on investments had no way to 
repatriate their profits 
shanghais market is a model of what chinese leaders hope to do 
generally as they reform the economy borrow western tools but keep 
socialist principles of central control the center uses price as a 
balancing tool but has little else in common with western 
financial markets 
playing the market for profit is not allowed prices are set in 
isolation from world markets and even from markets in other cities 
in china 
still its come a long way since 1986 then businessmen had to 
find their own partners to buy or sell currency the center was 
just a place to register the deal and prices varied widely 
the currency exchange markets in other cities still stick to 
this model but in 1988 shanghai advanced to a more systematic and 
auctionlike way of trading four mornings a week banks and 
companies that are registered as members bring their buy and sell 
orders to the center 
the center tallies them up when dollar supply exceeds demand 
it lowers the price of a dollar by one fen onehundreth of a yuan 
every two minutes until some sellers withdraw or buyers enter 
when demand for dollars exceeds supply the price is raised the 
price is fixed when buy and sell offers balance and all trades are 
made at the same price 
now its more fair said the centers deputy manager wang 
deshun a thin talkative man who once worked for chinas central 
bank information is open and everyone can watch the movement of 
prices and decide whether to enter the market or not 
thats the theory in practice the government tightly controls 
who can trade and for what purposes new regulations such as a 
ban on importing luxury cars directly affect dollar demand and 
therefore the exchange rate 
the center also can reject traders if the gap between supply and 
demand is too large or the central bank can step in and make up 
the difference wang said it has done so about 10 times 
historically dollars have gone from a high of 78 renminbi in 
september 1988 when import spending was freer to a low of 498 
reached last november when the governments tight loan policy 
forced many companies to sell dollar reserves 
we have to consider the interests of buyers and sellers 
wang said if the price for dollars goes too high many 
companies wont be able to buy dollars they need and if it falls 
too sharply thensellers wont be able to pay their debts 
because the center invariably devalues the renminbi from the 
official exchange rate economists say it at least achieves a rate 
closer to the real buying power of the two currencies for years 
china has kept its renminbi artificially high 
but some foreign businessmen say all the controls just make the 
center rate a second official rate set to serve the interests of 
state trade companies they are the main dollar sellers and benefit 
from the centers high dollar price while foreign joint ventures 
buy dollars to repatriate profits or import parts 
it dilutes our profits all we want is for them to let us 
exchange our renminbi at the official rate said the disgruntled 
american manager of one joint venture factory who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
like some other joint ventures he tried another way of getting 
dollars by buying a chinese product to sell abroad he made his 
purchase and lined up a hong kong buyer then the buyer disappeared 
now he has several tons of frozen chinese jelly fish sitting in 
a warehouse hes back to the currency market 
