the european parliament voted 
wednesday for a total ban on tobacco advertising throughout the 12 
nation european community 
but the ban will not take effect because the european 
communitys executive commission refused to accept the parliaments 
addition of the ban to proposed legislation to regulate tobacco 
advertising 
the parliament had added the tobacco advertising ban as an 
amendment to legislation proposed by the executive commission that 
would allow advertisers to show only the tobacco package and 
nicotine and tar yields in ads 
under ec law parliamentary amendments must be approved by the 
commission before they can be adopted on a majority vote by the ec 
governments if the commission fails to approve the amendments 
they can only be adopted on a unanimous vote by the ec governments 
a unanimous vote to ban tobacco advertising is highly unlikely 
because at least two members west germany and britain oppose such 
a ban 
however vasso papandreou the ec commissioner for social 
affairs said she would introduce new proposals after 1992 to ban 
tobacco advertising 
the current proposal should go into force at the end of 1991 
under the legislation proposed by the commission every tobacco 
advertisement would be required to carry a health warning covering 
at least 10 percent of the advertising space and more if the 
warning were in more than one language 
in addition tobacco advertisements in magazines aimed at those 
under 18 years old would be prohibited and indirect advertising 
such as putting tobacco brands or symbols on nontobacco products 
would also be banned 
