<DOCNO> AP900314-0195 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us sprint on wednesday announced a joint 
venture with two soviet organizations to provide sprints 
international data network services in the soviet union by late 
1990 
kansas city mobased sprint said it had signed a preliminary 
agreement with the central telegraph of the soviet ministry of 
posts and telecommunications and the institute of electronics and 
computer science of the latvian academy of sciences to form a new 
company known as telenet ussr 
voice communications are not involved in the agreement 
the pact calls for telenet ussr to operate a switching center in 
moscow to be connected with the sprintnet international data 
network it also will provide domestic and international electronic 
messaging services and distribute sprints telenet product line of 
data communications equipment in the soviet union 
details of the joint venture including financing will be 
agreed on by midyear the company said with telenet ussr 
operations expected to begin by the end of the year 
the pact requires approval by soviet and us government 
authorities 
sprint international president paolo guidi said his company was 
delighted to be part of the perestroika process that is 
building economic bridges between east and west 
sprint declined to disclose the cost of its involvement in the 
venture 
wednesdays announcement follows one in december in which 
denverbased us west said it would join with the soviet phone 
ministry and seven other international companies to build a 
fiberoptic telecommunications line across the soviet union at a 
cost of about 500 million 
commerce department secretary robert mosbacher whose department 
shares responsibility for issuing export licenses to us 
companies has indicated the adminstration would look favorably on 
us wests request as long as the soviets do not receive the very 
latest in us fiber technology 
the united states historically has taken a hard line on exports 
of products that may be used militarily by soviet bloc nations but 
with the recent decline of communism in eastern europe president 
bush has said hes willing to review export contraints contained in 
the coordinating committee on multilateral export controls 
central telegraph serves 120000 soviet telex subscribers and 
4000 international customers the latvian group is involved in 
computer data communications 
syd courson a sprint spokesman in kansas city said it was too 
early to predict how much money would be generated from the soviet 
venture in addition it is not known how the soviets will overcome 
their shortage of western currency to pay for sprints services and 
equipment 
sprint which created its reston vabased sprint international 
division on jan 1 plans to establish switching centers in 20 
foreign markets this year 
its transatlantic traffic is carried by the ptat1 fiber cable 
that sprint coowns with britains cable and wireless plc ptat1 
which began operating last fall was the first privately funded 
transatlantic fiber cable system its ability to handle 80000 
simultaneous transmissions is double the capacity of the tat8 
fiber cable owned by the american telephone amp telegraph co and 
stateowned phone companies in europe canada and australia 
in another announcement wednesday sprint also said it intends 
to be part of a group of companies planning to build a 260 million 
fiberoptic cable linking japan china hong kong and singapore 
it has not been determined whether sprint will have an ownership 
position or purchase capacity on the cable which will carry voice 
data and video signals 
sprints international ambitions reflect the growing financial 
strength of united telecommunications inc of westwood kan 
sprints majority owner united telecom posted operating income of 
910 million in 1989 up from 2528 million in 1988 
sprints international telecommunications revenues are growing 
20 percent a year considerably faster than domestic revenues 
</TEXT>
