<TEXT>
a rush to reach business agreements 
with east germany is livening up the current leipzig trade fair 
with a bonn cabinet minister predicting an avalanche of 
germangerman joint ventures will emerge from this years event 
west german carmakers volkswagen general motorsowned opel and 
daimlerbenz the stuttgartbased maker of luxury cars and heavy 
trucks have jumped on the bandwagon detailing joint venture deals 
with east germanys ifa automobile works 
others among the 1000 west german companies vying for 
jointventure agreements and other deals at the weeklong fair 
include the thyssen ag industrial concern electronics company 
siemens and precision optics firm zeiss which reportedly is 
negotiating a reunification with its east german counterpart 
carl zeiss 
the west german rush to sign preliminary agreements underlines 
the confidence of managers that german unification is near and 
there are profits to be made in rebuilding east germany which is 
in economic shambles after 40 years of communist rule 
last falls peaceful popular revolt that ousted hardline leaders 
has set the stage for the new age of germangerman business 
relations 
the leipzig fair is the oldest international trade fair in the 
world dating back more than 800 years and is one of the biggest 
some 60 countries are participating in the spring edition of the 
twiceannual event which focuses on industrial equipment and 
electronics with the number of west german companies up by 25 
percent from last year 
west german economics minister helmut haussmann has predicted 
an avalanche of joint ventures following east germanys first 
free elections sunday after which the unification process is 
expected to quicken 
a day after the fair opened last sunday volkswagen announced 
details of the biggest deal so far at the current gathering a 
5050 joint venture agreement with ifa 
the companies plan to start modernizing ifas antiquated 
trabants which use twostroke engines and became famous as the 
smokebelching transport of for the hordes of east germans that 
moved westward when the borders opened ifas factory at zwickau 
already is producing engines for the west german company 
later trabant production will be phased out and vws polo and 
golf models will be built at zwickau vw president carl hahn said 
vw plans total investments of 294 billion by 1994 when about 
1000 cars per day should be coming off the assembly line hahn 
said initial investments of 353 million are planned for the 
plant which hopes to be making about 50 polo models a day by 
december 
daimlerbenz and ifa also signed an agreement at the fair monday 
to build heavy trucks but details of the planned joint venture 
were still being worked out 
the same applies to opel which said it was working on a 
preliminary agreement with ifas wartburg automobile plant located 
in the east german city of eisenach near the border with west 
germany 
other deals at the fair include preliminary agreements between 
siemens and a state electronics combine in dresden to produce 
industrial robots thyssen will join with another east german 
congolomerate takraf to produce building elevators and waste 
processing plants 
one of east germanys largest combines the 60000worker carl 
zeiss company of jena reportedly is in secret negotiations with 
the west german zeiss company set up by the former owners of carl 
zeiss after the east german communists expropriated them 
the two companies are holding talks at the fair on joint 
manufacture of computer chips and optical equipment a 
reunification that could create one of the worlds largest 
producers of hightech electronics the munich newspaper 
sueddeutsche zeitung said wednesday 
