<DOCNO> AP900314-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission accused a 
new york brokerage firm wednesday of using illegal sales practices 
to induce investors to buy overthecounter securities 
a civil lawsuit brought by the sec alleged that wellshire 
securities inc operated as a penny stock boiler room from july 
1988 to the present selling speculative overthecounter 
securities through highpressure sales pitches and illegal means 
that violated securities laws 
the lawsuit in us district court in manhattan charged that 
wellshire made exorbitant price predictions gave out false 
information about stocks made unauthorized sales and tried to stop 
clients from selling securities 
in one case listed in the complaint a 68yearold retiree was 
persuaded to borrow money from a home equity loan to buy securities 
wellshires president robert cohen and executive vice 
president carol martino were accused of knowing about and 
encouraging the illegal sales practices three of wellshires 
present and former brokers also were named in the lawsuit 
we are reviewing the allegations and we have no comment 
cohen said when reached by telephone in his office 
wellshire with six branch offices in long island new jersey 
florida georgia and germany has about 50000 customer accounts 
and employs 100 brokers the sec said 
the lawsuit also names two companies whose stock wellshire 
promoted ventura inc of needham mass which had entertainment 
and insurance subsidiaries and environmental landfills inc the 
owner of a landfill site in upstate plattekill 
the sec said ventura chairman robert beck and its director 
richard sand misrepresented venturas profitability and made 
fraudulent earnings predictions this information was given to 
wellshire whose brokers passed it on to investors the lawsuit 
alleges 
sand said he had no comment on the lawsuit beck was said to be 
unavailable 
environmental landfills and its chairman paul v winters were 
accused of making false and misleading statements about the legal 
status of the landfill regulatory approval of its cleanup and the 
likelihood of the landfills opening 
this information was published in wellshires inhouse market 
letter and used to spur investments the lawsuit said 
efforts to obtain comment from environmental landfills were 
unsuccessful because the company had no telephone listing 
a temporary restraining order that bars wellshire cohen and 
martino from any further securities law violations was signed 
wednesday by us district judge kevin duffy the order also 
freezes the defendants assets and requires they produce an 
accounting of their finances 
</TEXT>
